class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1);
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return dfs(0, -1, g, values);
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
```

This code first builds the graph based on the given edges, then it sums up all the values in the tree. After that, it performs a depth-first search on the tree, calculating the maximum score by considering the values on the path from the root to any leaf node. The function `dfs(x, fa, g, values)` calculates the maximum score of the subtree rooted at node `x`, while the `maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values)` is the entry point of the program.

